We first have to identify which transactions “represent” interest income. In our data the only items that “produce” interest income are the entries whose type is “Interest Receivables.” (Normally when interest is earned by the business the accrued interest is recorded as receivable.) Then we sum up the “amount” from each such row.

It turns out there are 30 such entries. (The first few have larger values – this is common many companies have higher interest earned in the very first days or the numbers are set by the system; then for later dates the amounts “step down.”)

We now sum them step‐by‐step:

1. First four entries (Jan 1–Jan 4):
  420.08 + 375.58 = 795.66  
  795.66 + 346.68369627 = 1142.34369627  
  1142.34369627 + 291.07612692 = 1433.41982319

2. Add the Jan 5 value:
  1433.41982319 + 235.21708718 = 1668.63691037

3. Next, the “Jan 6–Jan 12” period has 7 entries each with 199.61708718:
  7 × 199.61708718 = 1397.31961026  
  1668.63691037 + 1397.31961026 = 3065.95652063

4. Then Jan 13 and Jan 14 (2 entries at 190.71708718 each):
  2 × 190.71708718 = 381.43417436  
  3065.95652063 + 381.43417436 = 3447.3906950

5. For Jan 15–Jan 19 we have 5 entries at 164.01708718 each:
  5 × 164.01708718 = 820.0854359  
  3447.3906950 + 820.0854359 = 4267.4761309

6. Finally, for Jan 20–Jan 30 there are 11 entries at 135.53708718 each:
  11 × 135.53708718 ≈ 1490.907959  
  4267.4761309 + 1490.907959 = 5758.3840899

Thus, the total interest income (i.e. the sum of all Interest Receivables amounts) is about 5758.38.
